04280nam a22006735i 9781442666450DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20182014onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426664507 a10.3138/97814426664502doi  a(DE-B1597)496996  a(OCoLC)1046607184  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 7aSOC0250002bisacsh04a361.30922231 aMorton, Suzanne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWisdom, Justice and Charity :bCanadian Social Welfare through the Life of Jane B. Wisdom, 1884-1975 /cSuzanne Morton. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2018] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (328 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Saint John: Religion, Philanthropy, and the Poor Law, 1884–1909 -- tChapter Two. McGill: The Ethos of Female Service, 1903–1911 -- tChapter Three. Montreal: Charity, Philanthropy, and Social Service, 1903–1912 -- tChapter Four. New York City: Private Agency Work, 1910–1916 -- tChapter Five. Halifax: Bureaucratization, Emergencies, and the Progressive State, 1916–1921 -- tChapter Six. Montreal and Cape Breton: Social Work Training and Professionalization, 1921–1939 -- tChapter Seven. The Women’s Directory of Montreal and Private Agency Work, 1923–1939 -- tChapter Eight. Glace Bay: Exploring Public Welfare, 1940–1952 -- tConclusion. Sutherland’s River, 1952–1975 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOne of Canada’s first social workers, Jane B. Wisdom had an active career in social welfare that spanned almost the first half of the twentieth century. Competent, thoughtful, and trusted, she had a knack for being in important places at pivotal moments. Wisdom’s transnational career took her from Saint John to Montreal, New York City, Halifax, and Glace Bay, as well as into almost every field of social work. Her story offers a remarkable opportunity to uncover what life was like for front-line social workers in the profession’s early years.In Wisdom, Justice, and Charity, historian Suzanne Morton uses Wisdom’s professional life to explore how the welfare state was built from the ground up by thousands of pragmatic and action-oriented social workers. Wisdom’s career illustrates the impact of professionalization, gender, and changing notions of the state – not just on those in the emergent profession of social work but also on those in need. Her life and career stand as a potent allegory for the limits and possibilities of individual action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aSocial servicezCanadaxHistory. 0aSocial workerszCanadavBiography. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015z978311060681240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144266645040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442666450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442666450.jpg  a978-3-11-060681-2  University of Toronto Press Pilot 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK